transportation and communication costs fall. Paradoxically, however, cities have become increasingly important, and even within cities industrial clusters remain vital. Agglomeration Economics brings together a group of essays that examine the reasons why economic activity continues to cluster together despite the falling costs of moving goods and transmitting information. The studies cover a wide range of topics and approach the economics of agglomeration from different angles. Together they advance our understanding of agglomeration and its implications for a globalized world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aBusiness networksvCongresses. 0aIndustrial clustersvCongresses. 0aIndustrial locationvCongresses. 0aRegional economicsvCongresses. 0aSpace in economicsvCongresses. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aBaicker, Katherine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChandra, Amitabh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCombes, Pierre- Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuranton, Gilles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlaeser, Edward L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlaeser, Edward L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGobillon, Laurent, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGyourko, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHolmes, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Matthew E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerr, William R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKolko, Jed, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/